    public abstract class ProductModelBuilderBase<T extends ProductModelClass,B extends ProductModelBuilderBase>
extends java.lang.Object
    Base data "builder" class. Provides a facility for setting up property values and creating beans with those values.

    When create executes, properties and populators are set and executed in ascending order according to their "order" values. Those with the same order value are executed according to the order in which they were set or added.

      • set

        protected final <V> void set(ProductModelField<V,? super T> field,
                             V value)
        Sets the value to assign to a property when a new bean is created. The property is set with an order value of DEFAULT_ORDER. The behavior of this method depends on the property. There are three general classes of property: link, array, and scalar.

        If the property is a link (aka "foreign key") property, then the value may either be a KeyableBean, a Key, a DataBuilder, or null.

        If the property is an array property, then the value may either be a Collection, an array, or null. If it is null, or an empty collection or array, then the array is cleared, i.e., all previously added elements are removed (and DEFAULT_ORDER is used as the order value for all further elements added for that property). Otherwise, the collection or array may contain any combination of non-null values allowed for link properties (KeyableBean, Key, or DataBuilder).

        If the property is a scalar property, then the value must either be an instance of the property type, a ValueGenerator for the property type, or null.

        Parameters:
        field - the field to be set
        value - the value to set the field to
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - under any of the following circumstances:
        • The property is not a datamodel property.
        • The property does not exist on this builder's entity type.
        • The value is not compatible with the property type. E.g., the value is a number, but the property is of type String.

        protected final <V> void set(int order,
                             ProductModelField<V,? super T> field,
                             V value)
        Sets the value to assign to a property when a new bean is created. The behavior of this method depends on the property. There are three general classes of property: link, array, and scalar.

        If the property is a link (aka "foreign key") property, then the value may either be a KeyableBean, a Key, a DataBuilder, or null.

        If the property is an array property, then the value may either be a Collection, an array, or null. If it is null, or an empty collection or array, then the array is cleared, i.e., all previously added elements are removed (and order becomes the order value for further elements added for that property). Otherwise, the collection or array may contain any combination of non-null values allowed for link properties (KeyableBean, Key, or DataBuilder).

        If the property is a scalar property, then the value must either be an instance of the property type, a ValueGenerator for the property type, or null.

        Parameters:
        order - used to select when this property gets set on the object being created
        field - the field to set
        value - the value to set
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - under any of the following circumstances:
        • The property is not a datamodel property.
        • The property does not exist on this builder's entity type.
        • The value is not compatible with the property type. E.g., the value is a number, but the property is of type String.

        Adds an element to an array property. Allows subclasses to "incrementally" build up an array. If this is the first element to be added for this property, then the property will be set with order value DEFAULT_ORDER; otherwise, the order value from the first element to be added is used.

        element - the element to add to the array
        Throws:

        • The property is not an array property.
        • The element is not compatible with the property's component type.
